\section*{ACUTE INFLAMMATION}
- Acute inflammation is a rapid response to injury or microbes and other foreign substances that is designed to deliver leucocytes and plasma proteins to sites of injury.
- The major local manifestations of acute inflammation are;
a) vascular dilatations (causing erythema and warmth)
b) extravasation of plasma fluid and protein (oedema)
c) leucocytes emigration and accumulation at site of injury

\section*{i. Vascular changes}
1. Changes in blood flow and caliber

These begin early after tissue injury but develop but develop at varying rates depending on the severity of injury. They are characterized by;
a) Transient vasoconstriction of arterials.
- This is an inconstant finding and in mild injury it disappears within $3-5$ seconds but in severe injury such as burns, it may last several minutes.
- The mechanism is unknown; it may be neurogenic due to axonal reflex.
b) Persistent vasodilatation;
- Which firstly involves arterials and then results in opening of new micro-vascular beds in the area. Mediators include prostaglandins and nitric oxide.
- The blood flow thus will increase in injured and the volume of blood there will be 10 fold the normal level, this called active hyperaemia, which is the hallmark of the early haemodynamic changes in acute inflammation and it is the cause of hotness and redness which is observed clinically in acute inflammation.
- This stage of increased blood flow will last for $10-15$ minutes and is caused by chemical mediators such as histamine and serotonin (5-HT); these are liberated from the tissues during their damage.
2. Changes in vascular permeability
- Once the vasodilatation has started, plasma proteins which include fibrinogen will pass through the gaps between the endothelial cells.
- Increased vascular permeability is caused by;
- Endothelial gap formation
a) Endothelial cell contraction
- Which is irreversible process elicited by chemical mediators e.g. histamine, bradykinin, leukotriens and others. These bind to specific receptors on endothelial cell surface.
- It lasts 15-30 minutes and only affects venules.
b) Junctional retraction
- Which is a reversible process caused by chemical mediators like TNF and IL1, which induce structural reorganization of the cytoskeleton of cells.
- It lasts for 4-6 hours.
- Endothelial cell injury
- Direct
- Leucocyte mediated
- Direct endothelial cell injury is caused directly e.g. by burn or infection; it lasts for 2-12 hours.
- Leucocyte dependent injury results from accumulation of leucocytes during inflammation; leucocytes will be activated and release toxic oxygen metabolites and proteolytic enzymes.
c) Increased transcytosis (vesicular trafficking).
d) Angiogenesis

\section*{Cellular response}
- Normal blood flow is characterized by axial flow in which the plasma is seen near vessel wall and cellular components (RBC, WBC, platelets) occupying the central column.
- In case of acute inflammation, the red cells and more importantly, white cells will become more closely packed near the vessel wall especially in the venules, this is
called margination of leucocytes. Some of the leucocytes may pass through the vessel wall and migrate into the extra vascular space of an inflamed area.
a) Sticking
- The WBC adheres in great number to endothelial surface of blood vessels. The binding is due to presence of the adhesion moelecules on the leucocytes and endothelial cell surface.
b) Emigration 11111

