- This is the process by which mobile WBC escape from the blood vessels into the peri-vascular space and tissues (PMN).
- They pass by their amoeboid movement into the endothelial junctions.
c) Chemotaxis
- This refers to the directional movement of cells towards an attractant.
- Chemotactic agents include:
- Exogenous or endogenous substance like soluble bacterial product
- Component of complement system
- Cytokines as IL-8
d) Phagocytosis
- Phagocytosis and release of lysosomal enzymes are two of the major benefits occurring from the accumulation of the leucocytes at the site of inflammation.
- There are three distinct steps in phagocytosis:
- Recognition and attachment
- Engulfment
- Killing/degradation/digestion.

\section*{1). Recognition and attachment of the particle to be ingested by the leukocytes:}

Phagocytosis is enhanced if the material to be phagocytosed is coated with certain plasma proteins called opsonins. These opsonins promote the adhesion between the particulate material and the phagocyte s sell membrane. The three major opsonins are:
- The Fc fragment of the immunoglobulin, components of the complement system
- C3b and C3bi, and
- The carbohydrate-binding proteins - lectins.

Thus, IgG binds to receptors for the Fc piece of the immunoglobulin $(\mathrm{FcR})$ whereas
3cb and 3bi are ligands for complement receptors CR1 and CR2 respectively.
2). Engulfment: During engulfment, extension of the cytoplasm (pseudopods) flow around the object to be engulfed, eventually resulting in complete enclosure of the particle within the phagosome created by the cytoplasmic membrane of the phagocytic cell.

As a result of fusion between the phagosome and lysosome, a phagolysosome is formed and the engulfed particle is exposed to the degradative lysosomal enzymes.
3) Killing or degradation: The ultimate step in phagocytosis of bacteria is killing and degradation. There are two forms of bacterial killing
a). Oxygen-independent mechanism: This is mediated by some of the constituents of the primary and secondary granules of polymorphonuclear leukocytes. These include:
- Bactericidal permeability increasing protein (BPI)
- Lysozymes
- Lactoferrin
- Major basic protein
- Defenses

It is probable that bacterial killing by lysosomal enzymes is inefficient and relatively unimportant compared with the oxygen dependent mechanisms. The lysosomal enzymes are, however, essential for the degradation of dead organisms within phagosomes.
b) Oxygen-dependent mechanism: There are two types of oxygen- dependent killing mechanisms
i) Non-myeloperoxidase dependent

The oxygen - dependent killing of microorganisms is due to formation of reactive oxygen species such as hydrogen peroxide ( H 2 O 2 ), super oxide ( O 2 ) and hydroxyl ion ( $\mathrm{HO}-$ ) and possibly single oxygen (102). These species have single unpaired electrons in their outer orbits that react with molecules in cell membrane or nucleus to cause damages. The destructive effects of H 2 O 2 in the body are gauged by the action of the glutathione peroxidase and catalase.
ii) Myloperoxidase dependent

The bactericidal activity of H 2 O 2 involves the lysosomal enzyme myeloperoxidase, which in the presence of halide ions converts H 2 O 2 to hypochlorous acid ( HOCI ). This H 2 O 2 - halide myecloperoxidease system is the most efficient bactericidal system in neutrophils. A similar mechanism is also effective against fungi, viruses, protozoa and helminths.

Like the vascular events, the cellular events (i.e. the adhesion, the transmigration, the chemotaxis, \& the phagocytosis) are initiated or activated by chemical mediators.

\section*{Cardinal signs of acute inflammation}
1) Swelling (tumor) - this is due to oedematous fluid accumulation.
2) Redness (rubor) - this is due to hyperaemia because of vasodilation.
3) Hotness (calor) - this is due to because of vasodilatation and slowing of the blood, so it will give heat locally to the affected area.
4) Pain (dalor) this is due to stimulation of nerve ending of the affected area by bacteria or tissue toxin.
